One more note --
I used to write (and I have seen a lot of others write) tests like this:
// Assuming a simple actor like ...
class ObjectUnderTest {
    private final Dependency dependency;
    ObjectUnderTest(Dependency dependency) {
        this.dependency = dependency;
    }
    Value lookupValue() {
        return dependency.getValue();
     }
}

// Here, we mock out all dependencies of the unit, and write a test
// that basically just re-codifies or implementation logic into Mockito syntax.
public final class AnemicUnitTest {
    private Dependency dependency;
    @Before
    public void setup() {
        this.dependency = mock(Dependency.class);
        this.objectUnderTest = new ObjectUnderTest(dependency);
    }

    @Test
    public void lookupValueCallsDependency() {
        when(dependency.getValue()).thenReturn(Value.of(2));
        assertEquals(Value.of(2), doSomething.lookupValue());
    }
}

This is an "anemic" unit test, where all dependencies are mocked. We've verified that the unit of code (the ObjectUnderTest) calls our Dependency. But so what? The complexity is very low.
Now, let's imagine Dependency is something like TensorFlow, and getValue() triggers thousands of lines of code to be executed. If we can avoid using the mock, we have a bonafide component test on our hands, and a good indication that the ObjectUnderTest itself will work in a real-world application.
// Here, we test *both* ObjectUnderTest, and the direct dependencies it needs to its job
public final class ComponentTest {
     private RealDependency dependency;
     private ObjectUnderTest objectUnderTest;

     @Before
      public void setup() {
          this.dependency = new RealDependency();
          this.objectUnderTest = new ObjectUnderTest(dependency);
      }

      @Test
      public void lookupValueReturnsExpectedValue() {
          // Value is not arranged, but derived form real world business conditions
          dependency.setColor("#441155"); // Some logic mutates the dependency state
          assertTrue(Value.of(44), objectUnderTest.getValue());
      }
}

